`crates/ctx-cage` is the offline sandbox crate: it runs an agent subprocess under `bwrap` with a masked filesystem, fresh namespaces, and no egress except a proxied API relay, then guarantees teardown. Depending on it means either shelling out to the `ctx-cage`/`ctx-run` binaries or embedding `lifecycle::execute(&Resolved) -> Result<i32, CageError>` and `bwrap::build_bwrap_args` directly.

The crate has three parts. `src/` is the implementation, split cleanly along the cage boundary (host-side CLI/bwrap/proxy/runtime/lifecycle vs. guest-side broker/spawn/protocol), with `summarize.rs` as an unrelated post-run concern. `assets/` supplies the two static payloads the sandbox injects verbatim at runtime — an nsswitch config and the agent's system-prompt doctrine (`cage-rules.md`) — which must stay synchronized with tool names and NSS sources actually present in the cage; nothing here is parsed, so a rename in `src/` silently breaks the prompt unless the asset is updated too. `tests/` exercises each subsystem in isolation, with `common/` as the only shared fixture (synthetic `BwrapConfig`) and duplicated (not shared) socket-uniqueness and shape-mirroring conventions against `bwrap`, `cli`, and `proxy`.

Crate-wide invariants that span these directories: `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` must never enter cage env (both `src/proxy.rs` and `src/runtime.rs` depend on this); `target_root` is canonicalized once and used verbatim everywhere (bwrap binds, trust-map key, git-dirty check); secrets/masks are always empty regular files, never `/dev/null`; and `CAGE_RULES_MD` (compiled from `assets/cage-rules.md`) must be passed via `--append-system-prompt-file` on every real `claude` launch — any new launcher path or asset rename has to preserve that link across `src/lib.rs`, `assets/`, and the launcher code together.

No `intent.md` exists at any level, so no divergence can be assessed.